---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FetchCallout from "../../components/FetchCallout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Phius Certification Guide — PH-Tools Docs" activeLib="guides">
  <div class="guide-page">
    <header class="guide-head">
      <div class="guide-head__crumb">
        <span>Guides</span>
        <span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span>
        <span class="current">Phius Certification</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="guide-head__title">Managing Phius Passive House Certifications</h1>
      <p class="guide-head__desc">
        Phius certification is an iterative review process that requires managing a complex folder structure,
        parsing multi-sheet Excel feedback forms, and cross-referencing dozens of technical documents. This page
        explains the certification workflow and provides reference material for navigating projects, understanding
        review status, and responding to feedback items.
      </p>
    </header>

    <article class="article guide-article">
      <h2 id="reference-docs">Phius Certification Reference Documents</h2>
      <p>
        We maintain two reference documents specifically formatted for AI tools and certification workflows.
        These are plain markdown files — no HTML, no front-matter — containing folder maps, Feedback Form
        parsing rules, and review status interpretation.
      </p>
      <p>
        These docs are hosted at stable URLs on this site. When we update the folder structure or form version
        guidance, anyone using these URLs gets the current version automatically.
      </p>

      <FetchCallout
        url="https://docs.passivehousetools.com/llm/guides/phius-certification/folder-map.md"
        description="Phius project folder structure — standard hierarchy, file naming conventions, and what each folder contains."
      />

      <FetchCallout
        url="https://docs.passivehousetools.com/llm/guides/phius-certification/feedback-form-guide.md"
        description="Feedback Form parsing guide — workbook structure, sheet names, column layout, status interpretation, and file path resolution."
      />

      <h2 id="using-with-any-tool">Using These Docs with Any AI Tool</h2>
      <p>
        The reference docs above work with any AI tool that can read a URL or accept pasted text.
        Here are some common approaches:
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tool</th>
            <th>How to use</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>ChatGPT</strong></td>
            <td>Paste the reference doc URL into your prompt — ChatGPT will fetch and read it. Or copy the markdown content directly into your message.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Cursor / Windsurf</strong></td>
            <td>Add the reference doc URL as context using <code>@URL</code>, or save the markdown file locally and add it with <code>@file</code>.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>GitHub Copilot Chat</strong></td>
            <td>Paste the reference doc content into the chat, or save it locally in your project and reference it.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Claude Code</strong></td>
            <td>Use <code>WebFetch</code> to pull the doc into context, or install a pre-built skill (see <a href="#claude-code-skills">below</a>) that does this automatically.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Any other tool</strong></td>
            <td>Copy the markdown content from the URL and paste it into your AI conversation as context.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        The key idea is the same regardless of tool: give the AI the reference material <em>before</em>
        asking it to work with your Phius project, parse the Feedback Form, or navigate certification documents.
        Think of it like handing someone the project template and the current feedback sheet before asking them
        to work on a certification round.
      </p>

      <h2 id="common-workflows">Common Certification Workflows</h2>
      <p>
        Here are typical tasks you might ask an AI tool to help with using these reference docs:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Summarize review status</strong> — "Parse the Feedback Form and tell me which sections have open items"</li>
        <li><strong>Find specific files</strong> — "Where's the ERV datasheet for unit 1-1?" (locating files by type and unit number)</li>
        <li><strong>Cross-reference feedback items</strong> — "The feedback says 'see .../2. Datasheets & Specs/...' — verify the file exists and extract the relevant value"</li>
        <li><strong>Draft responses</strong> — "For assembly type RT-01, the reviewer asked about U-value. Read the thermal calculation PDF and draft a response citing the right file path."</li>
        <li><strong>Track changes between rounds</strong> — "Compare the R3 and R4 feedback forms and summarize what's changed"</li>
      </ul>

      <hr />

      <h2 id="claude-code-skills">Claude Code Skills</h2>
      <p>
        If you use <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claude Code</a>,
        you can install <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>skills</strong></a>
        that automatically load the right reference docs when a Phius certification task comes up.
        This section is Claude Code&ndash;specific — if you use a different AI tool, the
        <a href="#reference-docs">reference docs</a> and <a href="#using-with-any-tool">general guidance</a> above
        are all you need.
      </p>

      <h3 id="how-skills-work">How Skills Work</h3>
      <p>
        A <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener">skill</a>
        is a markdown file that Claude Code loads when a task matches its trigger description.
        Each skill contains a compact instruction set plus <code>WebFetch</code> commands that pull the
        full reference docs from this site at runtime.
      </p>
      <p>The flow looks like this:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>You ask Claude about a Phius certification task</li>
        <li>Claude loads the skill's <code>SKILL.md</code> — a ~100-line instruction set with quick-reference tables</li>
        <li>The skill tells Claude to <code>WebFetch</code> the full reference docs from <code>docs.passivehousetools.com/llm/guides/phius-certification/...</code></li>
        <li>Claude now has the complete project structure and parsing rules in context for the rest of the task</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Because the reference docs are hosted here, they stay current — when we update the folder structure
        or Feedback Form version guidance, every skill user gets the update on their next task. No reinstall,
        no version mismatch.
      </p>

      <h3 id="available-skills">Available Skills</h3>

      <div class="skill-cards">
        <div class="skill-card">
          <div class="skill-card__head">
            <span class="skill-card__name">phius-certification</span>
            <a class="skill-card__dl" href="/skills/phius-certification.md" download>Download SKILL.md</a>
          </div>
          <p class="skill-card__desc">
            Navigate Phius certification project folders, parse the Feedback Form, track review status,
            and cross-reference documentation. Use when working on certification review cycles, managing
            feedback items, or locating supporting documents.
          </p>
          <div class="skill-card__meta">
            <span>Fetches:</span>
            <code>folder-map.md</code>, <code>feedback-form-guide.md</code>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 id="installation">Installation</h3>
      <p>
        Skills live in your
        <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code/skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claude Code skills directory</a>.
        Each skill is a folder containing a <code>SKILL.md</code> file.
      </p>

      <h4>Option A: Manual download</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Download the skill file using the link above</li>
        <li>Create the skill directory: <code>mkdir -p ~/.claude/skills/phius-certification</code></li>
        <li>Move the downloaded file: <code>mv phius-certification.md ~/.claude/skills/phius-certification/SKILL.md</code></li>
      </ol>

      <h4>Option B: One-liner</h4>
      <pre><code># Install phius-certification skill
mkdir -p ~/.claude/skills/phius-certification && \
  curl -sL https://docs.passivehousetools.com/skills/phius-certification.md \
  -o ~/.claude/skills/phius-certification/SKILL.md</code></pre>

      <h4>Verify</h4>
      <p>
        After installation, the skill should appear in Claude Code's skill list. You can verify by running
        <code>ls ~/.claude/skills/</code> — you should see the phius-certification directory.
      </p>
      <p>
        To test, start a Claude Code session in a Phius project folder and ask it to "summarize the open items
        in the latest Feedback Form" or "where's the ventilation datasheet?" It should automatically load the
        skill, fetch the reference docs, and help with the task.
      </p>

      <h2 id="related-skills">Related Skills</h2>
      <p>
        The <code>phius-certification</code> skill works well alongside these other skills for complete certification workflows:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>wufi-xml</strong> — Verify values in the WUFI-Passive energy model against feedback items</li>
        <li><strong>pdf</strong> — Extract data from cut-sheets, datasheets, and drawings referenced in the Feedback Form</li>
        <li><strong>xlsx</strong> — Parse the Feedback Form Excel workbook and build summaries</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <footer class="site-footer">
      <div class="site-footer__left">
        <span>PH-TOOLS</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <a href="https://github.com/PH-Tools">GitHub</a>
      </div>
      <div class="site-footer__right">
        <span>docs.passivehousetools.com</span>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
